  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening local capacities to improve rural livelihoods</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In the last decade, cycles of droughts and floods have caused enormous impact in the region, especially in the marginalized population in El Salvador and the response mechanisms have been limited. More recently the tropical storm 12 E affected 95% of the country, especially the people who live along the Pacific coast. According to CEPAL, 2011the economic damage is estimated at around U$ 134.5 million. In this country 93% of the population live in rural areas and poverty levels are high, with some 47.21% of the population living in extreme poverty (less than a dollar a day). Most families are subsistence peasant farmers &#x2013; some own small plots of land and others rent land located on badly eroded hillsides and often employing unsustainable farming practices, with a heavy use of and dependence on chemical inputs and imported seed. Access to credit or technical support for small producers is practically non-existent. Added to this, the community organisation and participation in political processes is weak and the involvement of women and young people is particularly poor. Structures at local level are not articulated at municipal level. This project aims to promote the sustainable livelihoods with a DRR approach. It will focus in strengthening organizational and productive processes, promoting a vision of sustainable development through the implementation of alternative, agro ecological techniques which protect and preserve the environment. It will ensure the full involvement of women and young people, strengthening their voice and leadership.
 On the theme of risk management the project aims to activate community committees to respond to emergency and disaster situations in the 12 communities. These bodies will be trained on important themes such as the legal framework for disaster prevention, the roles of each structure of this community committee in disaster risk reduction, the incorporation of the perspective of risk management, the importance of preparedness and mitigation in community planning.  

This project is looking to increase levels of food security and improve the socio-economic conditions of 12 rural communities in the municipality of Guaymango, through strengthening local organisational structures, promoting sustainable agricultural practices and incorporating the risk management approach, thereby improving the resilience capacity to an emergency and reducing vulnerability to disasters.</narrative>
  </description>
